 1. Story Context
This document captures my analysis of PLIG-6999 and the solution approach I followed, based directly on the requirement walkthrough by Mariela and the architecture established by Jose in the prior story PLIG-6815 (Authorized Signer).
1.1 Background
During grooming, Mariela explained that this story is functionally almost identical to the Authorized Signer automation already built. The ask is to extend the existing Financial Account Role → Relationship Center framework to cover two new roles, with two additional qualifying conditions layered on top.
Jose assigned the story to me directly because I built the Authorized Signer framework and already understand the relationship-linking logic, the reciprocal role lookups, and the trigger/queueable pattern in place.
1.2 Why Reuse Matters Here
•	The trigger (FinancialAccountRoleTrigger) does not need to change — it already dispatches both after-insert and after-delete to the handler.
•	The relationship-building logic (ACR / CCR / AAR routing by Individual vs Business) is identical to the Authorized Signer story.
•	Reciprocal Roles for “Escrow Agent” and “Joint Owner” were already created in a prior release — no new metadata work needed.
•	Picklist values for both roles were already added to AccountContactRelation and ContactContactRelation — deployment of data model changes is already done.
This meant my job was scoped narrowly: add new filtering criteria on top of an existing, proven framework — not redesign anything.
2. Requirement Analysis
2.1 Core Trigger Condition
A Relationship Center record should be created only when ALL of the following are true on a newly inserted Financial Account Role:
1.	Role = “Escrow Agent” OR Role = “Joint Owner”
2.	The related Financial Account’s Record Type = Deposit
3.	The Financial Account’s Special Case field = IOLA, IOLTA, or Fiduciary
If any one of these three conditions fails, no relationship record should be created — this was explicitly called out by Mariela using two negative examples (Escrow Agent on a Loan account, and Joint Owner on a Deposit account with Special Case = Standard).
