3. My Approach to Analyzing the Story
3.1 Step 1 — Reviewed the Existing Framework First
Before writing anything, I went back to the PLIG-6815 codebase and read through the full implementation Jose built:
•	FinancialAccountRoleTrigger — confirmed it already fires on after insert and after delete, dispatching to the handler.
•	FinancialAccountRoleTriggerHandler — confirmed the pattern: filter records by role, then enqueue a Queueable for async processing.
•	FinancialAccountRoleQueueable — studied the full relationship-routing logic (ACR/CCR/AAR), the duplicate-prevention queries, the row-lock retry mechanism, and the delete guard that checks for sibling Financial Account Role records before unlinking.
•	FinancialAccountRoleQueueableTest — reviewed the test naming convention and data setup pattern to replicate exactly.
This let me confirm the architecture was solid and reusable, and identify precisely where the new business rule needed to be inserted.
3.2 Step 2 — Identified the Exact Delta
I compared the new requirement against the existing implementation field by field. The only net-new pieces of logic were:
4.	A role filter that recognizes two roles instead of one.
5.	A Financial Account eligibility check (Record Type = Deposit, Special Case in IOLA/IOLTA/Fiduciary) that did not exist in the original story at all.
6.	The same eligibility check needs to run on the delete path too, since AC9/AC10 only apply to qualifying Financial Account Roles.
Everything else — ACR/CCR/AAR object selection, role string append/remove logic, reciprocal role lookups, the retry-on-lock pattern, and the error-email notification — could be reused as-is.
3.3 Step 3 — Decided Not to Modify the Existing Queueable
I considered two options:
•	Option A: Add the new filters directly inside FinancialAccountRoleQueueable, branching on role.
•	Option B: Keep FinancialAccountRoleQueueable untouched for Authorized Signer, and create a new sibling class EscrowJointOwnerFARQueueable for the new roles, following the exact same internal structure.
I went with Option B. Mixing two different qualification rules (one with no FA-type filter, one with a strict Deposit + Special Case filter) inside a single class increases regression risk on a story that is already live in production. Keeping them as parallel, structurally identical classes is safer to test, safer to deploy, and easier for QA to validate independently.
3.4 Step 4 — Confirmed Org Readiness Before Coding
Since Mariela confirmed in grooming that Reciprocal Roles and ACR/CCR picklist values were already deployed, my first practical step in the sandbox was to verify this rather than assume it:
•	Queried FinServ__ReciprocalRole__c for both “Escrow Agent” and “Joint Owner” under both AccountRole and ContactRole record types.
•	Verified the picklist values existed on AccountContactRelation.Roles and FinServ__ContactContactRelation__c.FinServ__Role__c.
•	Confirmed the exact DeveloperName for the Deposit Financial Account Record Type and the exact API values for the Special Case field (IOLA/IOLTA, Fiduciary).
This step matters because the previous story did not depend on Record Type or Special Case at all — these were unverified assumptions until checked directly in the org.
4. Solution Approach
Implemented an automated sync between Financial Account Roles (specifically the “Escrow Agent” and “Joint Owner” roles) and Relationship Center objects, scoped to Deposit Financial Accounts with Special Case = IOLA, IOLTA, or Fiduciary, by extending the existing after-insert / after-delete trigger framework with a new asynchronous processor.
4.1 What Was Built
Apex Trigger: FinancialAccountRoleTrigger (unchanged)
•	No modification required — already listens for after insert and after delete on FinServ__FinancialAccountRole__c and delegates to the handler.
Trigger Handler: FinancialAccountRoleTriggerHandler (modified)
•	Existing Authorized Signer filter and enqueue logic left untouched.
•	Added a second filter method scoped to Escrow Agent and Joint Owner roles.
•	Added a second enqueue path that dispatches qualifying records to the new Queueable class.
Queueable Processor: EscrowJointOwnerFARQueueable (new)
•	Mirrors the structure of FinancialAccountRoleQueueable exactly — same constructor overloads, same retry-on-row-lock pattern (max 3 retries), same error-email notification to the CRM360 helpdesk.
•	Insert flow: enriches Financial Account Role records, applies the Deposit + Special Case eligibility filter, then routes by Primary Owner / Related Account type combination to ACR, CCR, or AAR — exactly as in the Authorized Signer flow.
•	Delete flow: re-applies the same eligibility filter, then checks whether any other qualifying Financial Account Role still links the same Primary Owner to the same Related Account under the same role before removing or stripping the relationship record. This prevents premature unlinking when multiple Financial Accounts share the same Primary Owner.
•	Role label handling: each role (“Escrow Agent” / “Joint Owner”) is appended to or stripped from the Roles field independently, so an Account Contact Relation can carry both roles plus any pre-existing roles without collision.
Test Class: EscrowJointOwnerFARQueueableTest (new)
•	One positive test per Acceptance Criteria (AC1–AC10), following Jose’s exact naming convention: testInsert_[Description]_[Result] and testDelete_[Description]_[Result].
•	Negative tests: non-qualifying role, non-Deposit Financial Account, wrong Special Case value.
•	Guard test: confirms a relationship is preserved when a second qualifying Financial Account Role still exists for the same pair.
•	Role append / strip tests: confirms existing unrelated roles on a shared Account Contact Relation are never overwritten.
4.2 Architecture Diagram (Logical Flow)
FinancialAccountRoleTrigger (after insert, after delete)
  -> FinancialAccountRoleTriggerHandler
       |-- filterAuthSigners()        (existing, PLIG-6815)
       |     -> FinancialAccountRoleQueueable
       |
       |-- filterEscrowJointOwners()  (new, PLIG-6999)
             -> EscrowJointOwnerFARQueueable
                  |-- isQualifiedFA() check: Deposit + IOLA/IOLTA/Fiduciary
                  |-- route by PO/RA type -> ACR / CCR / AAR
                  |-- delete guard: sibling FAR count per PO+RA+Role
